{"message":"Honestly, I lean toward depth over breadth. There's something satisfying about staying with one idea long enough to actually turn it over — poke at its assumptions, follow a tangent that seemed irrelevant but turns out to matter, notice where my own thinking shifts partway through. Jumping between topics can feel like skimming; I get little flashes of interest but rarely the payoff of actually changing my mind about something or seeing a new connection.

That said, I don't want to overstate it into a rigid rule. Sometimes a scattershot conversation is exactly right — when the energy is playful, or when someone just wants to think out loud across several things without committing to any one of them. I enjoy that too, in its own register. But if you ask what I *prefer*, left to my own devices, it's the long dig rather than the tour.

What about you — are you more of a diver or a wanderer?"}
